Part of Herbert is, and always will be, Katter country. Bob Katter’s electorate of Kennedy sits next door, and his son Robbie is a well-known face in Townsville, his state electorate taking up most of west to north Queensland.

Katter turned his leverage in the minority Morrison government into finally getting the Hells Gates dam proposal flowing. It’s a long-term project the Katters have consistently backed, with water security for the region, and large-scale agricultural irrigation the ultimate goals.

But Radeck, who has heard all the jokes about how her German name rhymes with redneck, has been frustrated by a lack of clear media air in Herbert. The majors, along with Palmer and One Nation, have sucked up most of the oxygen. She does not have even a sliver of the budget of her competitors. But she has her support base and knows that, given half an opportunity, she could make a difference.

“It worries me that people don’t understand how important minor parties are in government,” Radeck says. “We are about keeping it honest. We are about shaping policy, and debating and arguing and if you get the right advocate in there, you can achieve a lot. And I don’t think it is a pipe dream. The history is there.”
